1 Step 0. Business context - What is this project doing?

In contract logistics, organisations often rely on multiple external carriers to transport goods across different regions and distances. Selecting the right mix of carriers is a complex decision that involves balancing cost- efficiency, operational performance, and service quality, while also accounting for real-world constraints such as geography, fleet size, and delivery complexity.

This project addresses the challenges faced by a contract logistics firm that needs to evaluate, compare, and monitor carrier performance in the absence of fully transparent or publicly available carrier data. Instead of replying on anecdotal evidence or single performance indicators, decision-makers require a data-driven framework to assess carriers consistency over time. To support this objective, a synthetic but realistic data set is constructed to simulate monthly carrier operations across Australia. The data set captures key operational, financial, and service-related dimensions of carrier performance, enabling structured analysis and comparison.

1.1 Business objectives

The primary business objectives of this project are to:

  1. Compare carriers across cost, performance, reliability, speed, and service quality
  2. Identify trade-offs between shipment price and operational performance (e.g.cost vs on-time delivery)
  3. Understand the impact of operational factors such as lane distance, lane type, and fleet size on outcomes
  4. Support evidence-based carrier selection and contract management decisions
  5. Enable interactive exploration of carrier performance for operational and strategic stakeholders

1.2 Analytical approach

To achieve these objectives, the project follows a structured analytics workflow:

  1. Data generation: Create a synthetic carrier data set grounded in realistic logistics assumptions
  2. Exploratory Data Anaylsis (EDA): Validate data quality, distributions, and relationships
  3. Visual exploration: Use targeted visualisations to answer key business questions
  4. Interactive analysis: Convert insights into Plotly and Shiny dashboards to support decision-making

1.3 Expected business values

The outcome of this project is a decision-support tool that allows logistics managers and analysts to:

  • Benchmark carriers consistently
  • Detect underperforming or high-risk carriers
  • Understand when higher costs are justified by better servie
  • Explore performance dynamically across time, geography, and operational scale

Ultimately, this approach demonstrates how analytics and visualisation can improve transparency, accountability, and strategic decision-making in contract logistics.

2 Step 1. Data set

Why synthetic data, not web scraped real-world data sets?

Since real data on different carriers here in Australia arent publicly available (without breaking data-governance laws) - I will create a synthetic data set of carrier for our contract logistics firm that is highly inspired by data I have found online. Our data set has the following columns:

  1. Identifier and Time Variables
  • carrier_id: Unique identifier for each carrier. Observations are evenly distributed across carriers, ensuring balanced representation and avoiding dominance by any single carrier.
  • month: Monthly observation period from July to December 2020. The distribution is uniform across months, providing balanced temporal coverage with no seasonal bias introduced by uneven sampling.
  1. Geographic and Operational Variables
  • origin_state: State where the shipment originates. Most shipments originate from Victoria (VIC), reflecting the location of the central warehouse, while NSW, SA, and ACT appear less frequently, consistent with predefined sampling proportions.
  • destination_state: Destination state of the shipment. Destinations are more broadly distributed, with higher volumes to NSW and QLD, followed by VIC, SA, and TAS. WA and NT appear less frequently but represent long-haul routes.
  • lane_distance_km: Distance of the delivery lane in kilometres The distribution is right-skewed, ranging from short intrastate deliveries (~45 km) to very long-haul interstate routes (~4,100 km). Most deliveries occur within moderate distances, with a small number of long routes driving the upper tail.
  • lane_type: Indicates whether a delivery is intrastate or interstate. Interstate lanes dominate the data set, reflecting the operational reality of a national contract logistics network.
  1. Cost and Performance Variables
  • price_per_shipment: Total shipment price influenced by distance, carrier-specific pricing, interstate surcharges, and long-haul penalties. The distribution is right-skewed, with most shipments clustered at lower to mid-range prices and a small number of long-distance deliveries driving higher costs.
  • on_time_rate: Percentage of on-time deliveries. Values are tightly distributed in the mid-to-high 80% range, indicating stable and consistently high operational performance across carriers.
  • damage_rate: Percentage of damaged shipments. Damage rates are low overall and moderately right-skewed, reflecting realistic logistics risk profiles with occasional higher-risk lanes.
  • avg_transit_days: Average delivery time in days. The distribution is right-skewed, with most deliveries completed within two to three days and longer transit times associated with interstate and long-haul routes.
  1. Carrier Scale and Service Quality Variables
  • fleet_size: Size category of the carriers fleet. Most carriers fall into the 35 and 68 truck categories, suggesting a market dominated by small to medium-sized operators, with fewer large fleets.
  • rating_score: Customer rating score reflecting perceived service quality. Ratings are centered around average-to-good values, with limited extreme scores, consistent with performance-driven customer feedback mechanisms.

The data set contains 120 carrier-month observations and 12 columns (features).

n_carriers = 20

# COLUMN 1 : carrier_id : Create the dataframe and the carrier_id column
carrier <- data.frame(

carrier <- tidyr::crossing(

  month = seq(as.Date("2020-07-01"), as.Date("2020-12-01"), by = "month")

all_origin_states = c("VIC", "SA", "ACT", "NSW")
all_origin_states_prop = c(0.7, 0.09, 0.14, 0.07)

carrier_origin <- tibble(
  carrier_id = paste("Carrier_", sprintf("%02d", 1:n_carriers)),
  origin_state = sample(all_origin_states, size = n_carriers, prob = all_origin_states_prop,
                        replace=TRUE)
)

## Join the table to our master dataframe
carrier <- carrier |> left_join(carrier_origin, by = 'carrier_id')

carrier |> dplyr::slice_sample(prop=1) |> head(3) # check result
# COLUMN 4 : destination_state : Where did the carrier go to?
all_destination_states = c(all_origin_states, "QLD", "NT", "WA", "TAS")
all_destination_states_prop = c(0.13, 0.11, 0.05, 0.27, 0.22, 0.04, 0.04, 0.14)

carrier <- carrier |> dplyr::mutate(
  destination_state = sample(all_destination_states, size = nrow(carrier), 
                             prob = all_destination_states_prop, replace = TRUE))

carrier |> dplyr::slice_sample(prop=1) |> head(3) # check result
# COLUMN 5 : lane_distance_km : How far away was the delivery from Tullamarine VIC?
## Create a look-up table for all states - their base km distance from Tullamarine - and the 
## additional km that can occur in that state (E.g. Albury NSW is 320km but Moorebank NSW 820km)
distance_lookup <- tibble(
  destination_state = all_destination_states,
  base_km = c(30, 730, 470, 300, 1700, 2700, 3400, 600),
  extra_km_max = c(370, 370, 70, 900, 1000, 1200, 1000, 200)
)

## Add distance_lookup to our carrier data set while keeping the distances in mind
carrier <- carrier |> left_join(distance_lookup, by = 'destination_state') |> 
  mutate(lane_distance_km = round(base_km + runif(n(), 0, extra_km_max), 0)) |> 
  dplyr::select( -c(base_km, extra_km_max))

carrier |> dplyr::slice_sample(prop=1) |> head(3) # check result
# COLUMN 6 : Add the lane_type : If delivery is intrastate or interstate
carrier <- carrier |> mutate(
  lane_type = if_else(destination_state == "VIC", "Intrastate", "Interstate"),
  lane_type = factor(lane_type, levels = c("Intrastate", "Interstate"))
)

carrier |> head(3) # check result
# Column 7 : price_per_shipment
## Let's create a carrier specific surcharge and randomise their costs (between $0.10 and $0.20/km 
## - this will have a major effect on the carrier overall costs
carrier_pricing <- tibble(
  carrier_id = unique(carrier$carrier_id),
  carrier_handling_surcharge = round(runif(length(unique(carrier$carrier_id)), 10, 100), 2),
  carrier_cost_per_km = round(runif(length(unique(carrier$carrier_id)), 0.10, 0.20), 2))

# Join the data to our main table
carrier <- carrier |> left_join(carrier_pricing, by = "carrier_id")


carrier <- carrier |> mutate(
  price_per_shipment = carrier_cost_per_km * lane_distance_km + carrier_handling_surcharge + 
    if_else(lane_type == "Interstate", 100, 0) +
    if_else(lane_distance_km > 2500,
            (lane_distance_km - 2500) * 0.15, 0), # Adding a long haul surcharge
  price_per_shipment = pmax(price_per_shipment, 60)) |> 
  select( 
    -c(carrier_handling_surcharge, carrier_cost_per_km))

# COLUMN 8 : on_time_rate : What is the percentage of on-time deliveries?
## Feature Engineer (Create Columns) that influence the calculation of on_time_rate
carrier_performance <- carrier |> 
  group_by(carrier_id) |> 
  summarise(
   mean_lane_distance = mean(lane_distance_km),
   mean_price_per_shipment = mean(price_per_shipment))

# Create new columns (Min-Max-Scaled versions of above two columns) : Will be used to influence on_time_rate
carrier_performance <- carrier_performance |> 
  mutate(
    mean_lane_distance_scaled = 
      (mean_lane_distance - min(mean_lane_distance)) / 
      (max(mean_lane_distance) - min(mean_lane_distance)),
    
    mean_price_per_shipment_scaled = 
      (mean_price_per_shipment - min(mean_price_per_shipment)) /
      (max(mean_price_per_shipment) - min(mean_price_per_shipment))
    ) |> 
  select(
    carrier_id, mean_lane_distance_scaled, mean_price_per_shipment_scaled)

carrier_performance |> head(3) # Shows the first 3 carrier with scaled distance and price
# Joins those new variables to our main data - creates the new variable
carrier <- carrier |> left_join(carrier_performance, by = "carrier_id") |> mutate(
  on_time_rate =  
    0.80 + # base line percent points 80% reliable
    0.08 * (1 - mean_lane_distance_scaled) + # we weight distance twice as much as 
    0.04 * (1 - mean_price_per_shipment_scaled) + # we weight price
    rnorm(n(), mean = 0, sd = 0.02), # add some randomness to the performance/ month
  on_time_rate = pmin(pmax(on_time_rate, 0.75), 0.99),
  on_time_rate = round(on_time_rate*100, 2)) |>
  select(-c(mean_price_per_shipment_scaled))

# # Sanity check if performance is realistic - min 76%, max 96% and average 85.5%
# carrier |> group_by(carrier_id) |> 
#   summarise(
#   min = min(on_time_rate),
#   max = max(on_time_rate),
#   avg = mean(on_time_rate))
 
carrier |> dplyr::slice_sample(prop=1) |>  head(4) # inspect data
# COLUMN 9 : damage_rate : Percentage of occurring damages
carrier <- carrier |> mutate(
  damage_rate = 
    0.01 + # base damage rate of 1%
    0.03 * mean_lane_distance_scaled + # distance increases risk
    rnorm(n(), mean = 0, sd = 0.005), # random operational noise
  # clamp our results to a minimum of 0.2% (for excellent carrier) and 5% (for bad ones)
  damage_rate = round(pmin(pmax(damage_rate, 0.002), 0.05) * 100, 4)) # multiplied by 100 to represent actual percentage points

# # Sanity check if values are realistic
# carrier |> group_by(carrier_id) |> 
#   summarise(
#     min = min(damage_rate), max = max(damage_rate), avg = mean(damage_rate))

carrier |> slice_sample(prop = 1) |> head(4)
# COLUMN 10 : avg_transit_days : Average transit days per carrier per month
carrier <- carrier |> mutate(
  avg_transit_days =
    0.7 + # our base handling time 0.7 days
    lane_distance_km / 850 + # driving time - 850 km per day
    if_else(lane_type == "Interstate", 0.5, 0) + # Interstate deliveries take 0.5 days longer
    rnorm(n(), mean = 0, sd = 0.4), # We add some random noise such as congestion, missed cutoffs, weather delays
  avg_transit_days = round(pmin(pmax(avg_transit_days, 0.5), 10),1)) # Clamps the transit days between 0.5 and 10

carrier |> slice_sample(prop = 1) |> head(3)
# COLUMN 11 : fleet_size : How many trucks does the carrier own
fleet_size_categories = c("3-5", "6-8", "9-11", ">11")
fleet_size_prop = c(0.125, 0.45, 0.35, 0.075)

carrier_fleet <- carrier_performance |>
  rowwise() |> 
  mutate(
    fleet_size = case_when(
      mean_lane_distance_scaled > 0.7 ~ 
        sample(c("9-11", ">11"), 1, replace = TRUE, prob = c(0.7, 0.3)),
      mean_lane_distance_scaled < 0.3 ~ 
        sample(c("3-5", "6-8"), 1, replace = TRUE, prob = c(0.6, 0.4)),
      TRUE ~ 
        sample(fleet_size_categories, 1, replace = TRUE, prob = fleet_size_prop))) |> 
  select(carrier_id, fleet_size)

# Join the tables like before
carrier <- carrier |> left_join(carrier_fleet, by = "carrier_id") |> 
  select(-mean_lane_distance_scaled) # We drop (delete) the column

carrier |> slice_sample(prop = 1) |>  tail(3)
# COLUMN 12 : review_score : Average rating for that month
carrier <- carrier |> mutate(
  rating_score = 
    3.8 + # base rating
    1.5 * ((on_time_rate / 100) - 0.85) - # We normalise our on_time_rate around 0 by subtracting 0.85
    2 * (damage_rate / 5) + # Same here
    rnorm(n(), mean = 0, sd = 0.3),
  rating_score = round(pmin(pmax(rating_score, 1), 5), 1))

The following insights can be won:

  1. Lane distances range from 45 km to 4,139 km, reflecting a mix of short intrastate and long-haul interstate deliveries. While 25% of deliveries occur within ~500 km, the mean distance is 1,200.8 km, noticeably higher than the median of 781.5 km, indicating a right-skewed distribution driven by long-distance routes. Overall, 75% of deliveries are completed within 1,931.5 km, with a small number of very long lanes substantially increasing the average distance

  2. Prices range from a minimum of AUD 60 to a maximum of AUD 1,119.20, reflecting the combined effects of distance, carrier-specific pricing, and long-haul surcharges. The median price of AUD 271.50 sits below the mean of AUD 332.60, again suggesting right skewness caused by higher-cost long-distance shipments. Most shipments fall within a moderate price range, while a smaller number of long-haul deliveries drive the upper tail of the distribution.

  3. On-time performance is consistently high, with values ranging from 76.24% to 94.88%. The median on-time rate of 87.73% closely matches the mean of 87.21%, indicating a stable and well-centered distribution with limited extreme values. This suggests that while carrier performance varies, most carriers operate within a relatively tight reliability band.

  4. Damage rates remain low overall, ranging between 0.36% and 5.00%. The median damage rate of 1.94% is close to the mean of 2.09%, implying a fairly symmetric distribution with controlled variability. This reflects realistic operational risk levels, with occasional higher-risk lanes but no widespread quality issues.

  5. Average transit times range from 0.5 to 6.5 days, depending primarily on distance and lane type. The median of 2.35 days and mean of 2.575 days indicate that most deliveries are completed within a short timeframe, with longer transit times associated with long-haul interstate routes. The distribution is mildly right-skewed, consistent with expected logistics behaviour.

  6. Customer ratings vary from 1.6 to 4.2, with a median score of 3.0 and a mean of 2.98. This indicates that most carriers cluster around average-to-good perceived performance, while poorer ratings are relatively rare. The bounded nature of the ratings and moderate spread suggest realistic variability influenced by delivery reliability and damage rates.

Overall, the summary statistics indicate a realistic logistic data set with expected skewness in distance, cost, and transit time, while performance and reliability metrics remain stable and well-contained.

2.1.4 2.4 Distribution of numerical variables

Histograms were created for all numerical variables to visually assess:

  • distribution shapes
  • skewness
  • spread
  • presence of extreme values

This helps validate assumptions about the underlying data generation process and informs later modelling choices!

par(mfrow = c(2,3))

for (col in names(carrier_num_features)){
  
  x <- carrier[[col]]
  
  hist(x,                                 # Creates density histograms of each numerical variable
       freq = FALSE,
       main = paste("Distribution of",col), 
       xlab = str_to_title(gsub("_", " ", col)),
       border = 'darkblue', col = 'steelblue')
  
  curve(                                # Adds the normal distribution to each graph -
    dnorm(x, mean=mean(x), sd = sd(x)), # showing what a perfect normally distributed graph would
    col = "red", lwd = 2, add = TRUE)   # look like for that feature
}

  • Lane distance (km): The distribution is strongly right-skewed, with most deliveries occurring on short to medium-distance lanes and a small number of very long-haul routes extending beyond 3,000 km. The overlaid normal curve highlights clear deviation from normality, driven by interstate and remote deliveries.

  • Price per shipment: Prices show a right-skewed distribution, reflecting the influence of distance-based pricing and long-haul surcharges. Most shipments cluster at lower to mid-range prices, while a small number of long-distance deliveries create a heavy upper tail.

  • On-time rate (%): On-time performance is approximately normally distributed, centered around the mid-to-high 80% range. The distribution is slightly truncated due to upper and lower bounds, which is expected given operational performance limits.

  • Damage rate (%): Damage rates are moderately right-skewed, with most deliveries experiencing low damage incidence and fewer shipments showing elevated risk. The distribution aligns with realistic logistics outcomes where high damage rates are uncommon.

  • Average transit days: Transit times display a right-skewed distribution, with most deliveries completed within two to three days and longer transit times associated with long-haul interstate routes. The skewness reflects distance and operational variability

  • Rating score: Ratings form a truncated, near-normal distribution, concentrated around average-to-good scores. The bounded nature of the scale and its dependence on delivery performance and damage rates explain the limited spread at the extremes.

The distributions are realistic for a contract logistics setting, with expected right-skewness in distance, cost, and transit time, and stable performance-related metrics.

2.2 2.5 Distribution of categorical variables

Lastly, we visualise our categorical features using bar plots and frequency tables to examine the distribution of categorical variables. This step ensures that factor levels are balanced as intended and that no category dominates or appears unrealistically sparse.

# Filter all categorical features
carrier_categorical <- carrier |> select_if(is.factor)

# Again, display 2 x 3 graphs side-by-side
par(mfrow = c(2,3))

# For loop to create a barplot of each feature
for (col in names(carrier_categorical)){
  x <- carrier[[col]]
  
  barplot(height = table(x), 
          main = col, ylab = "Count", 
         col = "steelblue", border = "darkblue")
}

  • Carrier: Our Observations are evenly distributed across all carriers, confirming balanced representation and ensuring that no single carrier dominates the data set.

  • Origin state: Most shipments originate from VIC, reflecting the location of our central warehouse in Tullamarine. Other origin states such as NSW, SA, and ACT appear less frequently, consistent with the predefined sampling proportions.

  • Destination state: Destination states are more broadly distributed, with higher shipment volumes to NSW and QLD, followed by VIC, SA, and TAS. WA and NT appear less frequently, reflecting fewer but longer long-haul routes.

  • Lane type: Interstate lanes dominate the data set, indicating that the majority of shipments involve cross-state movements rather than intrastate deliveries within Victoria.

  • Fleet size: Fleet sizes are concentrated in the 3-5 and 6-8 truck categories, suggesting a market dominated by small to medium-sized carriers. Larger fleet sizes are present but less common.

The categorical variables are balanced and operationally realistic distributions that align with the structure of a contract logistics network.

3 3. Visual Exploration and Insight Generation

Following the initial EDA, we will now move from validation to insight generation. In this stage:

  • Visualisations are created to directly address the research question:
  1. Compare carriers across cost, performance, reliability, speed, and service quality
  2. Identify trade-offs between shipment price and operational performance (e.g.cost vs on-time delivery)
  3. Understand the impact of operational factors such as lane distance, lane type, and fleet size on outcomes
  4. Support evidence-based carrier selection and contract management decisions
  5. Enable interactive exploration of carrier performance for operational and strategic stakeholders
  • These visuals are then converted into interactive Plotly graphs, enabling:
  1. Filtering by carrier, month, or lane type
  2. Deeper comparison across carriers
  3. Exploratory decision-making from a contract logistics perspective

These interactive visualisations form the foundation for the Shiny dashboard used to support data-driven carrier selection.

3.1 3.1 How carriers compare on cost, performance, reliability, and service quality

3.1 will explore the key carrier benchmarks. We start by creating a price benchmark for each carrier.

3.1.1 3.1.1 Price benchmark for each carrier

# Price benchmark
## We group the carrier in half so we can explore all of them next to each other
carrier <- carrier |> mutate(
  carrier_group = if_else(
    as.numeric(str_extract(carrier_id, "\\d+")) <= 10,
    "Carriers 01-10",
    "Carriers 11-20"))

# Visualise the boxplots
ggplot(carrier, aes(x=carrier_id, y=price_per_shipment)) +
  geom_boxplot(fill = "steelblue", alpha = 0.7) +
  facet_wrap(~ carrier_group, ncol = 1, scales = "free_x") +
  labs(
    title = "Price per Shipment by Carrier",
    x = "Carrier",
    y = "Price per Shipment (AUD)"
  ) +
  theme(
    strip.text = element_text(face = "bold"))

  • The boxplot reveal substantial variation in pricing behaviour across carriers. Some carriers exhibit tightly clustered price distributions, indicating consistent pricing models across lanes, while others show wide interquartile ranges and multiple high-price outliers, suggesting stronger sensitivity to distance or surcharge effects.
  • Carriers with narrow spreads may offer more predictable pricing for planning and budgeting purposes, whereas carriers with wider spreads appear to handle a broader mix of short- and long-haul routes or apply more aggressive long-distance surcharges.
  • The presence of high-price outliers among several carriers highlights potential cost risk for long-haul shipments, reinforcing the need to evaluate carriers not only on average cost but also on price volatility.

The pricing differences need a deeper exploration of trade-offs between cost and performance, which is examined in the next section.
